reasoning_4:
**Step 1: Multiply matrices**  
\[
\begin{bmatrix}
x & -2 \\
4 & y
\end{bmatrix}
\begin{bmatrix}
4 & 1 \\
y & x
\end{bmatrix}
=
\begin{bmatrix}
4x-2y & -x \\
16+y^2 & 4+xy
\end{bmatrix}
\]

**Step 2: Equate to RHS**  
\[
\begin{bmatrix}
4x-2y & -x \\
16+y^2 & 4+xy
\end{bmatrix}
=
\begin{bmatrix}
8 & -3 \\
20 & 10
\end{bmatrix}
\]

**Step 3: Solve**  
From \(-x = -3\): \(x = 3\).  
From \(16+y^2 = 20\): \(y = \pm 2\).  
Check \(y=2\): \(4(3)-2(2)=8\) and \(4+3\cdot2=10\) ✔.  
\(y=-2\) fails \(4x-2y=8\).

Thus \(x=3\), \(y=2\), so \(x-y=1\).

\[
\boxed{1}

